Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Equine infectious anaemia (EIA) is a persistent viral infection of equids. The causative agent, EIA virus (EIAV), is a lentivirus in the family Retroviridae, subfamily Orthoretrovirinae. Other members of the genus _Lentivirus_ include: bovine immunodeficiency virus; caprine arthritis encephalitis virus; feline immunodeficiency virus; human immunodeficiency virus 1; human immunodeficiency virus 2; and maedi/visna virus. EIA can be diagnosed on the basis of clinical signs, pathological lesions, serology and molecular methods. Infected horses remain viraemic carriers for life and, with very rare exceptions, yield a positive serological test result. Antibody response usually persists, and antibody-positive animals older than 6-8 months are identified as virus carriers (below 6-8 months of age, serological reactions can be due to maternal antibodies; status can be confirmed by molecular techniques). Infected equids are potential virus reservoirs. Biting flies are mechanical vectors for the virus in nature.

EIAV is not considered a risk for human health.

For the above and additional background information, including diagnostic methods and references, please refer to the OIE Terrestrial Manual 2014, Chapter 2.5.6 "Equine infectious anaemia" at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.05.06_EIA.pdf (adopted by the World Assembly of Delegates in May 2013).

In the previous EIA event, France reported 2 outbreaks. One outbreak occurred in the Department of Vaucluse (Provence-Alpes Cote d'zur region) and the 2nd was located in the Department of Gard (Languedoc- Roussillon region). See final report and map at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000012330_20130822_121910.pdf.

See a map of the French regions at http://www.ephotopix.com/image/europe/france_political_map.gif. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2862468,100.]
